Recent evidence suggests that in Escherichia coli, SecA/SecB and signal 
recognition particle (SRP) are constituents of two different pathways targeting 
secretory and inner membrane proteins to the SecYEG translocon of the plasma 
membrane. We now show that a secY mutation, which compromises a functional 
SecY-SecA interaction, does not impair the SRP-mediated integration of polytopic 
inner membrane proteins. Furthermore, under conditions in which the 
translocation of secretory proteins is strictly dependent on SecG for assisting 
