Factor-dependent transcription termination mechanisms are poorly understood. We 
determined a series of cryo-electron microscopy structures portraying the 
hexameric adenosine triphosphatase (ATPase) ρ on a pathway to terminating 
NusA/NusG-modified elongation complexes. An open ρ ring contacts NusA, NusG, and 
multiple regions of RNA polymerase, trapping and locally unwinding proximal 
upstream DNA. NusA wedges into the ρ ring, initially sequestering RNA. Upon 
deflection of distal upstream DNA over the RNA polymerase zinc-binding domain, 
NusA rotates underneath one capping ρ subunit, which subsequently captures RNA. 
