transporter. Random and site-directed mutation identified three point mutations 
(T394I, D398N, and K353A) in DcuB that caused a similar derepression as dcuB 
deletion, whereas the transport activity of the DcuB mutants was retained. 
Constitutive expression in the dcuB mutants depended on the presence of a 
functional DcuS-DcuR two-component system. Mutation of residues E79A, R83A, and 
R127A of DcuB, on the other hand, inactivated growth by fumarate respiration and 
transport of [14C]succinate, whereas the expression of dcuB'-'lacZ was not 
affected. Therefore, the antiporter DcuB is a bifunctional protein and has a 
regulatory function that is independent from transport, and sites for transport 
and regulation can be differentiated.

