Bacteria have many two-component signal-transduction systems (TCSs) that respond 
to specific environmental signals by altering the phosphorylated state of a 
response regulator. Although these systems are presumed to form an intricate 
signal network, the detailed mechanism of how they interact with each other 
remains largely unexplained. In a recent study of Salmonella, two TCSs have been 
discovered to be connected by a protein that protects a response regulator from 
dephosphorylation promoted by its cognate sensor kinase. This novel mechanism 
might provide an answer to some of the linkages found between other TCSs.

