transferring electrons to nitrogenase, and the rseC gene in the rpoE-rseABC 
operon. In-frame deletion of each open reading frame in the rsxABCDGE operon 
produced a similar constitutive phenotype. The double mutation of rsx and rseC 
suggested that rsxABCDGE and rseC gene products act together in the same pathway 
in reducing SoxR. Electron paramagnetic resonance analysis of SoxR and 
measurement of re-reduction kinetics support the proposal that rsx and rseC gene 
products constitute a reducing system for SoxR.

