In Gram-negative bacteria, outer-membrane integrity is essential for survival 
and is monitored by the σ(E) stress-response system, which initiates 
damage-repair pathways. One activating signal is unassembled outer-membrane 
proteins. Using biochemical and genetic experiments in Escherichia coli, we 
found that off-pathway intermediates in lipopolysaccharide transport and 
assembly provided an additional required signal. These distinct signals, arising 
from disruptions in the transport and assembly of the major outer-membrane 
components, jointly determined the rate of proteolytic destruction of a negative 
regulator of the σ(E) transcription factor, thereby modulating the expression of 
stress-response genes. This dual-signal system permits a rapid response to 
dysfunction in outer-membrane biogenesis, while buffering responses to transient 
fluctuations in individual components, and may represent a broad strategy for 
bacteria to monitor their interface with the environment.

