Toxin-antitoxins systems (TAS) are prokaryotic operons containing two small 
overlapping genes which encode two components referred to as toxin and 
antitoxin. Involvement of TAS in bacterial programmed cell death (PCD) is highly 
controversial. MazEF, a typical type II TAS, is particularly implicated in 
mediating PCD in Escherichia coli. Hence, we compared the metabolic fitness and 
stress tolerance of E. coli strains (MC4100 and its mazEF-derivative) which were 
extensively used by proponents of mazEF-mediated PCD. We found that both the 
strains are deficient in relA gene and that the ΔmazEF strain has lower fitness 
and stress tolerance compared to wild type MC4100. We could not reproduce mazEF 
mediated PCD which emphasizes the need for skeptic approach to the PCD 
hypothesis.

