The promoter of the gua operon has been located by transcript mapping using 
primer extension with reverse transcriptase. The surrounding nucleotide sequence 
has features characteristic of promoters under stringent and 
growth-rate-dependent regulation, namely a GC-rich discriminator next to the -10 
hexamer, an upstream AT-rich sequence (the UP element) and potential FIS-binding 
sites. Transcriptional activity of the gua promoter was examined using 
transcriptional fusions to lacZ placed at a single chromosomal location. 
Expression from gua was reduced under stringent conditions in vivo, and varied 
with growth rate. Growth-rate control was independent of guanine-mediated 
repression. A fusion in which the GC-rich discriminator was mutated by insertion 
of an AT-rich oligonucleotide was used to demonstrate the importance of this 
region in control. Both stringent and growth-rate-dependent controls were 
abolished by the mutation. Other potential regulatory signals in the vicinity of 
the gua promoter are a pur operator (binding site for the PurR repressor), a gua 
operator, a DnaA-binding site and a CRP/FNR-binding sequence. The gua promoter 
lies back-to-back with the promoter for xseA (exonuclease VII), the two 
promoters being separated by only 20 bp.

