mutations affecting DNA metabolism. In wild-type cells, DNA strands cut during 
cross-link removal were rejoined during a subsequent incubation into 
high-molecular-weight molecules. This rejoining was dependent on gene products 
involved in genetic recombination. A close correlation was found relating 
recombination proficiency, the rate of strand rejoining, and formation of viable 
progeny after DNA cross-linking by treatment with psoralen and light. Wild-type 
cells and other mutants which were Rec+ (sbcB, recL, recL sbcB, recB recC sbcA, 
